What is CSS?
    CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is a stylesheet language used to control the look and layout of web pages written in HTML. With CSS, you can change colors, fonts, spacing, alignment, layouts, animations, and responsiveness‚Äîwithout touching the HTML structure.

Why CSS is Important
    Separates design from content
    Makes websites beautiful and consistent
    Helps build responsive pages (mobile, tablet, desktop)
    Reduces repeated code
    Improves page loading and maintenance

Types of CSS : - CSS can be applied to HTML in three main ways:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Inline CSS
    CSS is written inside the HTML tag using the style attribute.
    Affects only one element.
example:
    <p style="color: red; font-size: 20px;">Hello World</p>
Advantages:
    Quick testing
    Highest priority
Disadvantages:
    Not reusable
    Makes HTML messy
    Hard to maintain
‚úÖ Use only for small or temporary changes

2Ô∏è‚É£ Internal CSS
    CSS is written inside the <style> tag in the <head> section.
    Applies to one HTML page.
Example:
    <head>
        <style>
            p {
                color: blue;
                font-size: 18px;
            }
        </style>
    </head>
Advantages:
    Better than inline CSS
    Useful for single-page styling
Disadvantages:
    Not reusable across multiple pages
‚úÖ Good for single-page websites or testing layouts

3Ô∏è‚É£ External CSS (Most Recommended)
    CSS is written in a separate .css file
    Linked to HTML using <link>
Example:
    HTML~ <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
    CSS~ p{
            color: green;
            font-size: 16px;
        }

Advantages:
    Clean HTML
    Reusable across many pages
    Easy maintenance
    Faster loading (browser caching)
Disadvantages:
    Requires extra file
‚úÖ Best practice for real websites and projects

CSS Priority Order (Important)
    If multiple CSS types are applied:
        Inline CSS > Internal CSS > External CSS

üéØ What is a Selector in CSS?
    A CSS selector is used to select (target) HTML elements so that styles can be applied to them.
Syntax:
    selector {
        property: value;
    }

üîπ Types of CSS Selectors (Most Important)
1Ô∏è‚É£ Element (Tag) Selector
    Selects all elements of a given type.
    h1 {
        color: blue;
    }
‚úî Applies to all <h1> tags

2Ô∏è‚É£ Class Selector
    Selects elements with a specific class
(Uses .)
    .box {
        background-color: yellow;
    }
<div class="box">Hello</div>
    ‚úî Can be used multiple times
    ‚úî Most commonly used

3Ô∏è‚É£ ID Selector
    Selects a unique element
(Uses #)
    #header {
        font-size: 24px;
    }
<div id="header">Title</div>
    ‚úî Used only once per page

4Ô∏è‚É£ Universal Selector
    Selects all elements
    * {
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
    }
    ‚úî Commonly used for CSS reset

5Ô∏è‚É£ Group Selector
    Applies same style to multiple selectors
    h1, h2, p {
        color: green;
    }

üîπ Advanced Selectors
6Ô∏è‚É£ Descendant Selector
    Selects elements inside another element
    div p {
        color: red;
    }
    ‚úî Selects <p> inside <div>

7Ô∏è‚É£ Child Selector
    Selects direct children only
    div > p {
        color: blue;
    }

8Ô∏è‚É£ Attribute Selector
    Selects elements with specific attributes
    input[type="text"] {
        border: 2px solid red;
    }

9Ô∏è‚É£ Pseudo-class Selector
    Used for special states
    a:hover {
        color: orange;
    }
Examples:
    :hover
    :active
    :focus
    :first-child

üîü Pseudo-element Selector
    Styles a part of an element
    p::first-letter {
        font-size: 30px;
    }
Examples:
    ::before
    ::after
    ::first-line






